VTo understand the business of mythology
p4
aVand what a Chief Belief Officer is supposed to do,
p5
aVyou have to hear a story
p6
aVof Ganesha,
p7
aVthe elephant-headed god
p8
aVwho is the scribe of storytellers,
p9
aVand his brother,
p10
aVthe athletic warlord of the gods,
p11
aVKartikeya.
p12
aVThe two brothers one day decided to go on a race,
p13
aVthree times around the world.
p14
aVKartikeya leapt on his peacock
p15
aVand flew around the continents
p16
aVand the mountains and the oceans.
p17
aVHe went around once,
p18
aVhe went around twice,
p19
aVhe went around thrice.
p20
aVBut his brother, Ganesha,
p21
aVsimply walked around his parents
p22
aVonce, twice, thrice,
p23
aVand said, "I won."
p24
aV"How come?" said Kartikeya.
p25
aVAnd Ganesha said,
p26
aV"You went around 'the world.'
p27
aVI went around 'my world.'"
p28
aVWhat matters more?
p29
aa(lp30
VIf you understand the difference between 'the world' and 'my world,'
p31
aVyou understand the difference between logos and mythos.
p32
aV'The world' is objective,
p33
aVlogical, universal, factual,
p34
aVscientific.
p35
aV'My world' is subjective.
p36
aVIt's emotional. It's personal.
p37
aVIt's perceptions, thoughts, feelings, dreams.
p38
aVIt is the belief system that we carry.
p39
aVIt's the myth that we live in.
p40
aa(lp41
V'The world' tells us how the world functions,
p42
aVhow the sun rises,
p43
aVhow we are born.
p44
aV'My world' tells us why the sun rises,
p45
aVwhy we were born.
p46
aVEvery culture is trying to understand itself:
p47
aV"Why do we exist?"
p48
aVAnd every culture comes up with its own understanding of life,
p49
aVits own customized version of mythology.
p50
aa(lp51
VCulture is a reaction to nature,
p52
aVand this understanding of our ancestors
p53
aVis transmitted generation from generation
p54
aVin the form of stories, symbols and rituals,
p55
aVwhich are always indifferent to rationality.
p56
aVAnd so, when you study it, you realize
p57
aVthat different people of the world
p58
aVhave a different understanding of the world.
p59
aVDifferent people see things differently \u2014
p60
aVdifferent viewpoints.
p61
aa(lp62
VThere is my world and there is your world,
p63
aVand my world is always better than your world,
p64
aVbecause my world, you see, is rational
p65
aVand yours is superstition.
p66
aVYours is faith.
p67
aVYours is illogical.
p68
aVThis is the root of the clash of civilizations.
p69
aVIt took place, once, in 326 B.C.
p70
aVon the banks of a river called the Indus,
p71
aVnow in Pakistan.
p72
aVThis river lends itself to India's name.
p73
aVIndia. Indus.
p74
aa(lp75
VAlexander, a young Macedonian,
p76
aVmet there what he called a "gymnosophist,"
p77
aVwhich means "the naked, wise man."
p78
aVWe don't know who he was.
p79
aVPerhaps he was a Jain monk,
p80
aVlike Bahubali over here,
p81
aVthe Gomateshwara Bahubali
p82
aVwhose image is not far from Mysore.
p83
aVOr perhaps he was just a yogi
p84
aVwho was sitting on a rock, staring at the sky
p85
aVand the sun and the moon.
p86
aa(lp87
VAlexander asked, "What are you doing?"
p88
aVand the gymnosophist answered,
p89
aV"I'm experiencing nothingness."
p90
aVThen the gymnosophist asked,
p91
aV"What are you doing?"
p92
aVand Alexander said, "I am conquering the world."
p93
aVAnd they both laughed.
p94
aVEach one thought that the other was a fool.
p95
aVThe gymnosophist said, "Why is he conquering the world?
p96
aVIt's pointless."
p97
aVAnd Alexander thought,
p98
aV"Why is he sitting around, doing nothing?
p99
aVWhat a waste of a life."
p100
aa(lp101
VTo understand this difference in viewpoints,
p102
aVwe have to understand
p103
aVthe subjective truth of Alexander \u2014
p104
aVhis myth, and the mythology that constructed it.
p105
aVAlexander's mother, his parents, his teacher Aristotle
p106
aVtold him the story of Homer's "Iliad."
p107
aVThey told him of a great hero called Achilles,
p108
aVwho, when he participated in battle, victory was assured,
p109
aVbut when he withdrew from the battle,
p110
aVdefeat was inevitable.
p111
aV"Achilles was a man who could shape history,
p112
aVa man of destiny,
p113
aVand this is what you should be, Alexander."
p114
aVThat's what he heard.
p115
aa(lp116
V"What should you not be?
p117
aVYou should not be Sisyphus,
p118
aVwho rolls a rock up a mountain all day
p119
aVonly to find the boulder rolled down at night.
p120
aVDon't live a life which is monotonous,
p121
aVmediocre, meaningless.
p122
aVBe spectacular! \u2014
p123
aVlike the Greek heroes,
p124
aVlike Jason, who went across the sea
p125
aVwith the Argonauts and fetched the Golden Fleece.
p126
aVBe spectacular like Theseus,
p127
aVwho entered the labyrinth and killed the bull-headed Minotaur.
p128
aVWhen you play in a race, win! \u2014
p129
aVbecause when you win, the exhilaration of victory
p130
aVis the closest you will come to the ambrosia of the gods."
p131
aa(lp132
VBecause, you see, the Greeks believed
p133
aVyou live only once,
p134
aVand when you die, you have to cross the River Styx.
p135
aVAnd if you have lived an extraordinary life,
p136
aVyou will be welcomed to Elysium,
p137
aVor what the French call "Champs-Élysées" \u2014
p138
aV(Laughter) \u2014
p139
aVthe heaven of the heroes.
