aa(lp141
VBut these are not the stories that the gymnosophist heard.
p142
aVHe heard a very different story.
p143
aVHe heard of a man called Bharat,
p144
aVafter whom India is called Bh\u0101rata.
p145
aVBharat also conquered the world.
p146
aVAnd then he went to the top-most peak
p147
aVof the greatest mountain of the center of the world
p148
aVcalled Meru.
p149
aVAnd he wanted to hoist his flag to say,
p150
aV"I was here first."
p151
aVBut when he reached the mountain peak,
p152
aVhe found the peak covered with countless flags
p153
aVof world-conquerors before him,
p154
aVeach one claiming "'I was here first' ...
p155
aVthat's what I thought until I came here."
p156
aVAnd suddenly, in this canvas of infinity,
p157
aVBharat felt insignificant.
p158
aVThis was the mythology of the gymnosophist.
p159
aa(lp160
VYou see, he had heroes, like Ram \u2014 Raghupati Ram
p161
aVand Krishna, Govinda Hari.
p162
aVBut they were not two characters on two different adventures.
p163
aVThey were two lifetimes of the same hero.
p164
aVWhen the Ramayana ends the Mahabharata begins.
p165
aVWhen Ram dies, Krishna is born.
p166
aVWhen Krishna dies, eventually he will be back as Ram.
